Democracy without Borders
In his 1848 speech supporting the extension of democracy to all American citizens regardless of race or wealth, Abraham Lincoln said,
> That it has pleased God to bestow these blessings upon us, and to put us in a position to appreciate them—we cannot avoid being grateful. We cannot help feeling it a pleasant duty to thank Almighty God for the good he had done to us.

In making this statement, Lincoln recognized that democracy is a blessing to be appreciated. He knew that democracy was, and always will be, an ongoing project, something that required constant attention, appreciation, and maintenance. In 2014, Barack Obama echoed this sentiment in his speech welcoming the French president to the White House. He stated:
> Our shared ideals and values are a beacon to the world. They are a source of hope for peoples striving for freedom and human dignity. And as nations that are rooted in the universal values of democracy and human rights, we are bound by our moral obligation, as individuals and as nations, to lead the way in standing up for this basic aspiration of all peoples. But we also know that the world is a complex place. And there will always be voices that argue for shirking our responsibilities, arguing that we're better off avoiding problems instead of confronting them. And that's why the alliance between our two nations is so essential. Together, we stand up for the human rights and dignity of all peoples, because that's who we are, and that's what we believe.

This chapter is about democracy as a value, or, perhaps more accurately, as the ultimate value for humanity. The argument here is that democracy is more than a political system or means for organizing a society. This is not to say that the actual political system, or the political mechanisms democracy entails, are not important. However, they are not ends in themselves, but means to achieve a value: a society where people enjoy freedom and their own human dignity, have the opportunity for personal development and creative endeavors, and are able to live their lives without fear and oppression. This chapter examines several dimensions of democracy as a value and how these dimensions are essential components of democracy in the twenty-first century.
**Democracy and Human Rights** Democracy is often linked with freedom, justice, and equality as its fundamental values. Democracy is also often seen as a means for protecting basic rights of citizens, such as property or freedom of expression, religion, and association. The United States Declaration of Independence, for example, cites three inalienable rights: life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. These rights are often known as human rights and democracy has proved, historically, to be one of the most effective ways to protect them. As Obama suggested in his comments above, democracy is more than an organizational tool; it is a way of realizing and protecting human rights.
The Universal Declaration of Human Rights reflects many values and ideals that democracy aspires to protect or promote. The Universal Declaration of Human Rights defines human rights as universal, indivisible, and interdependent for all people. The preamble to the declaration states:
> Whereas recognition of the inherent dignity and of the equal and inalienable rights of all members of the human family is the foundation of freedom, justice and peace in the world, [. . .] This Universal Declaration of Human Rights as a common standard of achievement for all peoples and all nations, to the end that every individual and every organ of society, keeping this Declaration constantly in mind, shall strive by teaching and education to promote respect for these rights and freedoms and by progressive measures, national and international, to secure their universal and effective recognition and observance, both among the peoples of Member States themselves and among the peoples of territories under their jurisdiction.

Freedom of speech, press, and religion are common elements of many democracies, as is respect for different lifestyles, and the promotion of social equality. Democracies also require a strong, independent judiciary that can help to ensure that individual rights are respected by other branches of government as well as by private actors. Democracies are also characterized by a commitment to the principles of the rule of law, equality before the law, and respect for the dignity of the individual. All of these values are central components not just of democracy, but of human rights. That is why democracy has been a powerful force for the advancement of human rights and the promotion of peace and development around the globe.
In fact, human rights and democratic development are closely intertwined. In addition to promoting basic human rights, democratization generates pressure for the recognition of a wider range of rights, including political rights and civil liberties. In addition, democratic institutions help to ensure the protection of human rights. Democracies are more likely to respect individual rights and liberties, including freedom of expression, religion, assembly, and the press. They are also more likely to protect minority rights and to promote civil and political liberties.
**Democracy and the Social Dimension** Democracy also has a social dimension that reflects the fact that human beings are social creatures. Democracy is not merely about protecting individual rights, but also about promoting the common good, ensuring equal access to opportunities, and fostering a sense of community. Social institutions and policies—such as social safety nets, public health programs, and public education systems—are important tools for promoting and protecting the social dimension of democracy.
Democracies also protect social rights, which reflect the rights to which individuals are entitled by virtue of their membership in a democratic society. Social rights are concerned not only with the individual's ability to live in dignity, but also with the person's integration into the broader social fabric. They are intended to ensure that each individual member of society has access to certain basic goods and services—such as health care, education, and social security—that are necessary for human beings to fulfill their basic needs and to participate fully in society.
**Democracy and the Global Dimension** Democracy is also evolving to meet new challenges that have arisen in the global age. The spread of democracy around the world has been one of the most remarkable developments of the past century. As the number of democracies has increased, the values of democracy have also become more universal, and their promotion more urgent. The democratic ideal is no longer limited to the domestic sphere of individual countries, but is increasingly becoming a goal of international relations.
The promotion of democracy has been an important element of American foreign policy for decades. The United States has actively supported democratic transitions in a number of countries, including the Philippines, South Korea, Nicaragua, and Eastern Europe. In addition, the United States and other democratic nations have played an active role in promoting democracy in various international institutions, such as the United Nations and the European Union. The promotion of democracy and the defense of human rights have also been major themes of the G8 summits, which bring together the leaders of the world's most industrialized nations.
The international dimension of democracy is also becoming more important because of globalization. In recent years, we have seen the emergence of transnational threats that are not limited to any particular nation or region. These include terrorism, weapons of mass destruction, pandemics, global warming, and organized crime. They pose a serious threat to democracy, to national security, and to the safety and well-being of individuals. For these reasons, it is increasingly important for nations to work together to meet these challenges. Democracies are well positioned to lead the way in this effort.
Conclusion
Democracy is a complex and evolving concept, reflecting a diverse range of values, institutions, and practices. It has a long and distinguished history, dating back to ancient Greece and Rome. In the centuries since, democracy has evolved, drawing on the experience of different cultures and different societies, and reflecting the changing realities of the world in which we live. Today, democracy is more widespread than at any time in history, and it is becoming increasingly relevant to the challenges of globalization and the promotion of universal human rights.
In the past, people have struggled long and hard for democracy, recognizing that it is not merely a political system, but a means of realizing the ideals of freedom, equality, and human dignity. As democracies continue to evolve and grow, they are facing new challenges, such as those related to globalization, terrorism, and the environment. They are also developing new practices and institutions to meet these challenges. Democracies are not fixed or frozen entities. They are, instead, dynamic and constantly changing systems that reflect the ongoing struggle to protect and promote the values that underlie them. Democracy remains the best means we know to make the world a better place.

Celtics coach Brad Stevens: 'We're not as good as we think we are'
Celtics coach Brad Stevens: ‘We’re not as good as we think we are’ originally appeared on NBC Sports Boston
For Celtics coach Brad Stevens, Thursday night’s 110-88 loss to the New York Knicks marked a wake-up call for Boston after a strong start to the season.
“We’re not as good as we think we are. That’s pretty clear,” Stevens said, per Steve Bulpett of The Boston Herald. “I’m not going to have any good answers for why we’re bad. I mean, I’ll take the fall. We’re not very good right now, and that’s on me as much as anything. I’ve got to figure out a way to help our guys get a little bit better.”
The Celtics entered Thursday’s contest atop the Eastern Conference with a 7-3 record, but Boston’s offensive struggles continued against the Knicks. The C’s shot just 39.6 percent from the field and 20.8 percent from 3-point territory.
Stevens specifically pointed to the Celtics’ execution on the offensive end as an area in need of improvement.
“When the ball moves, we’re a pretty good team offensively. When it sticks, we’re a bad team offensively,” he said. “…Whenever it moves consistently, things go well for us. We’ve been pretty good defensively, so we’ve kept ourselves in games, even when our offense has not been at the level it needs to be.”
The Celtics, who fell to 7-4 on the season, will next host the Oklahoma City Thunder on Friday night at TD Garden.

1. Tip the flour and salt into a large mixing bowl, then gradually whisk in the beer, stirring out any lumps, until smooth and free-flowing.
2. Add the dill, garlic and mustard to the batter and mix well.
3. Season the fish well on both sides with salt and pepper. Preheat your oven to 200°C/Gas Mark 6. Put the fish in the oven for 10 minutes, or until opaque (the fish will still be raw inside).
4. Meanwhile, heat 250ml of vegetable oil in a deep pan until a cube of bread dropped into it turns golden-brown in about a minute. This is for deep-frying, not shallow frying.
5. Carefully coat the fish pieces in the batter mixture and deep-fry them for about 7-10 minutes, or until the batter is crispy and golden, and the fish is cooked through to the core. Remove from the pan, drain excess oil and transfer to a plate ready to serve.
6. Serve with chips or mashed potato and mushy peas or tartare sauce.

# 새우작은과일박쥐

새우작은과일박쥐(Rhinopoma muscatellum)는 두더지과에 속하는 박쥐의 일종이다. 크기가 작고 육식성 박쥐로 큰 눈과 길고 큰 귀를 갖고 있으며, 작은 무리를 이루어 생활한다. 나뭇가지나 바위틈 등에서 은신하며, 낮에는 활동하지 않는다. 밤에 주로 나서서 곤충을 잡아먹는다. 사하라 이남 아프리카의 사막 지역과 사막 가장 가까운 지역에서만 서식하고 있다. 국제 자연 보전 연맹(IUCN)이 정한 멸종위기등급에서 관심을 필요로 하는 종으로 분류하고 있다.

The term “Southern food” is a bit of a misnomer. Dishes often classified as Southern cuisine are really a melting pot of flavors, incorporating influences from European, African, and Native American traditions. With its emphasis on fried dishes and slow-cooked, savory stews, Southern cooking is best known, perhaps, for its rich, satisfying flavor.
While it can often be heavy fare, there’s no reason you can’t get a little imaginative to create healthier takes on your favorite Southern dishes. This week, we’re sharing some of our favorite healthy Southern recipes. They’re every bit as crave-worthy as the originals, but with a fraction of the calories and fat!
One of our favorite ways to lighten up Southern-style dishes is to focus on the vegetable aspect of the dish. This hearty corn and shrimp chowder incorporates plenty of fresh corn, as well as shrimp for protein. The creamy soup can be made lower in fat by using low-fat milk, and by omitting the bacon (which we’ve never missed). While it’s easy to make a basic chowder recipe, this recipe is anything but basic. Full of flavor, it’s easily one of our favorite healthy Southern recipes.
This recipe for fried chicken may look a little complicated at first blush, but it’s actually pretty straightforward. You start by soaking the chicken in a buttermilk brine for 6 to 24 hours. While this step is a bit time-consuming, it helps the chicken soak up moisture, and makes it taste extra flavorful. After brining, you simply dredge and fry the chicken, then serve it up with your favorite sides (try it with mashed sweet potatoes or roasted Brussels sprouts for a healthy dinner!). Our favorite thing about this healthy Southern recipe? It only calls for 1 cup of oil, rather than the 4 to 5 cups you’d need for a traditional recipe.
As Southern staples go, you can’t get much more classic than a bowl of butter beans. This recipe for slow-cooked butter beans is one of our favorites. ## Description

The Rescuers is an animated film produced by Walt Disney Productions and first released on June 22, 1977 by Buena Vista Distribution. It was the 23rd film in the Walt Disney Animated Classics series and the first to be completed by the studio in a seven-year span without an executive producer (Woolie Reitherman had retired in late 1980). At 76 minutes, this film is the shortest Disney animated feature to have been produced by the studio.

The film is based on the book series by Margery Sharp, and was followed by a sequel, The Rescuers Down Under, in 1990. It is the most recently released Disney animated film to have been produced in the years before the Disney Renaissance.
The film contains several direct allusions to previous Disney films, including the Evil Queen from Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs and the Walrus and the Carpenter from Alice in Wonderland. In addition, the film's opening music is very similar to that used in Swiss Family Robinson, another film in which a group of like-minded animals sets out on a mission of mercy. The Rescuers was also the first of six Disney animated features released with the title sponsorship of Nestle. The following five features were: The Rescuers Down Under, Beauty and the Beast, Aladdin, The Lion King, and Pocahontas.

Their Venom GT was quite the head-turner and now, to beat all the odds, they have done it again: they made a 300mph car. It’s called the Venom F5 and it’s quite something.

The twin-turbocharged V8 engine delivers a ridiculous 1,600 horsepower output and with that, a claimed top speed of 301mph. It’s not just designed to go fast in a straight line, either. The Venom F5 has active aero and can generate over 2,000kg of downforce at 200mph.
Now, the main thing you’re thinking when looking at any supercar is: how much? Well, the answer is simple: $2.1 million. But, if you have that sort of cash and a desire for a very, very fast car, this is definitely for you. What’s even better is there’s no need to worry about it selling out because they are only making 24… ever. There are still 10 un-owned ones so get them while they’re hot!
